\begin_layout Subsection
Source material
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Per the NRL Formulary, let the rate-of-strain tensor be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W_{jk}=\frac{\partial v_{j}}{\partial x_{k}}+\frac{\partial v_{k}}{\partial x_{j}}-\frac{2}{3}\delta_{jk}\nabla\cdot v
\]

\end_inset

and this is intended to apply in the magnetic coordinates used there.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then define the viscous stress tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi$
\end_inset

: for a set of viscosity coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta^{species}$
\end_inset

, where arbitrarily we shall relabel 
\begin_inset Formula $z=b,\mbox{ }x=\perp,\mbox{ }y=\wedge$
\end_inset

 and from here on, the xyz notation of the magnetic coordinates is not used:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pi_{bb}=-\eta_{0}W_{bb}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pi_{\perp b}=-\eta_{2}W_{\perp b}-\eta_{4}W_{\wedge b}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pi_{\perp\perp}=-\frac{\eta_{0}}{2}\left(W_{\perp\perp}+W_{\wedge\wedge}\right)-\frac{\eta_{1}}{2}\left(W_{\perp\perp}-W_{\wedge\wedge}\right)-\eta_{3}W_{\perp\wedge}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pi_{\wedge b}=-\eta_{2}W_{\wedge b}+\eta_{4}W_{\perp b}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pi_{\wedge\wedge}=-\frac{\eta_{0}}{2}\left(W_{\perp\perp}+W_{\wedge\wedge}\right)+\frac{\eta_{1}}{2}\left(W_{\perp\perp}-W_{\wedge\wedge}\right)+\eta_{3}W_{\perp\wedge}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pi_{\wedge\perp}=-\eta_{1}W_{\perp\wedge}+\frac{\eta_{3}}{2}\left(W_{\perp\perp}-W_{\wedge\wedge}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Per the NRL Formulary, then we shall have (where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 shall mean momentum)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dp_{\alpha}}{dt}=m_{\alpha}n_{\alpha}\frac{dv_{\alpha}}{dt}+=-\nabla\cdot\Pi_{\alpha}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
mn\frac{dv_{x}}{dt}+=-\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\Pi_{xx}-\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\Pi_{xy}-\frac{\partial}{\partial z}\Pi_{xz}\label{eq:one}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

in magnetic coordinates.
 (Or perhaps transposed but it doesn't matter as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi$
\end_inset

 is symmetric.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Definition of viscosity coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Looking here at ion viscosity; electron is a bit different but not very.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, Braginskii 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega/\nu\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, fully ionised :
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{0}=0.96\frac{nT}{\nu}=0.96\eta_{*}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{2}=\frac{6}{5}\eta_{*}\frac{\nu^{2}}{\omega^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{4}=\eta_{*}\frac{\nu}{\omega}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

He has also 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{3}=\frac{1}{2}\eta_{4}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\frac{1}{4}\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

, exact for ions but only rough for electrons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Landau-Lifschitz Volume 10, Pitaevskii & Lifshitz, 1981 has 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{1}=\frac{2\pi^{1/2}\left(Ze\right)^{4}\lambda_{i}n_{i}^{2}}{5\left(MT\right)^{1/2}\omega_{ci}^{2}}=\frac{1}{4}\eta_{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{3}=\frac{nT}{2\omega_{ci}}=\frac{1}{2}\eta_{4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which gives a little idea of how the numerical factors might be arrived
 at(?).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is still a fair approximation for the electron tensor that 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\frac{1}{4}\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{3}=\frac{1}{2}\eta_{4}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
My speculative viscous stress tensor formula
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I have yet to get hold of a source that treats even the fully ionised case
 for general 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega/\nu$
\end_inset

; generally texts eschew the subject saying that the expressions are awkward.
 Instead we have the unmagnetised case and the highly magnetised case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we take the 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 from the left hand side then we see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\eta_{0}}{m}\propto\frac{nT}{m\nu}
\]

\end_inset

showing that 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{0}/m$
\end_inset

 is akin to the thermal conductivity 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
My speculative version for the general case, based on the Alfven-type conductivi
ty tensor that appears in the thermal conductivities, involves modifying
 only the viscosity coefficients:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{\parallel}=\eta_{0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{2}=\eta_{\perp}\approx\frac{1}{0.96}\frac{6}{5}\eta_{\parallel}\frac{\nu^{2}}{\omega^{2}{\color{blue}+\nu^{2}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{4}=\eta_{\times}=\frac{1}{0.96}\eta_{\parallel}\frac{\nu{\color{blue}\omega}}{{\color{blue}{\color{black}\omega}^{2}+\nu^{2}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{1}=\frac{1}{4}\eta_{2}\mbox{ ;}\mbox{ }\eta_{3}=\frac{1}{2}\eta_{4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Viscous effects and thermal conductivity are kindred processes (emphasised
 by Braginskii) so this guess seems reasonable - though we should get hold
 of a source to verify.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To go even further: we need to deal with multicomponent plasma.
 One obvious idea is to use the expressions from thermal conductivity to
 substitute for part of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{0}$
\end_inset

, so as to create dependence on neutral collisions (with viscosity cross
 section of course).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Zhdanov is the book that treats multicomponent, contains the definitive
 information but again looks at the high 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

-field case, using the Grad(1949) method of moments as with Balescu.
 Therefore a good way in the future might be to buy the Zhdanov book, use
 it for the multicomponent high-
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

-field case, and as here intuit what might happen for intermediate 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 fields.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now in my speculative (and for electrons, simplified) version let's rewrite
 :
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{bb}=-\eta_{\parallel}W_{bb}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{\perp b}=-\eta_{\perp}W_{\perp b}-\eta_{\times}W_{\wedge b}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Pi_{\perp\perp} & = & -\frac{\eta_{\parallel}}{2}\left(W_{\perp\perp}+W_{\wedge\wedge}\right)-\frac{\eta_{\perp}}{8}\left(W_{\perp\perp}-W_{\wedge\wedge}\right)-\frac{\eta_{\times}}{2}W_{\perp\wedge}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{\wedge b}=-\eta_{\perp}W_{\wedge b}+\eta_{\times}W_{\perp b}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Pi_{\wedge\wedge} & = & -\frac{\eta_{\parallel}}{2}\left(W_{\perp\perp}+W_{\wedge\wedge}\right)+\frac{\eta_{\perp}}{8}\left(W_{\perp\perp}-W_{\wedge\wedge}\right)+\frac{\eta_{\times}}{2}W_{\perp\wedge}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Pi_{\wedge\perp} & = & -\frac{\eta_{\perp}}{4}W_{\perp\wedge}+\frac{\eta_{\times}}{4}\left(W_{\perp\perp}-W_{\wedge\wedge}\right)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Or,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{bb}=-\eta_{\parallel}\left(2\frac{\partial v_{b}}{\partial b}-\frac{2}{3}\nabla\cdot v\right)\label{eq:bb}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{\perp b}=-\eta_{\perp}\left(\frac{\partial v_{\perp}}{\partial b}+\frac{\partial v_{b}}{\partial\perp}\right)-\eta_{\times}\left(\frac{\partial v_{\wedge}}{\partial b}+\frac{\partial v_{b}}{\partial\wedge}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Pi_{\perp\perp} & = & -\eta_{\parallel}\left(\frac{\partial v_{\perp}}{\partial\perp}+\frac{\partial v_{\wedge}}{\partial\wedge}-\frac{2}{3}\nabla\cdot v\right)-\frac{\eta_{\perp}}{4}\left(\frac{\partial v_{\perp}}{\partial\perp}-\frac{\partial v_{\wedge}}{\partial\wedge}\right)-\frac{\eta_{\times}}{2}\left(\frac{\partial v_{\wedge}}{\partial\perp}+\frac{\partial v_{\perp}}{\partial\wedge}\right)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{\wedge b}=-\eta_{\perp}\left(\frac{\partial v_{\wedge}}{\partial b}+\frac{\partial v_{b}}{\partial\wedge}\right)+\eta_{\times}\left(\frac{\partial v_{\perp}}{\partial b}+\frac{\partial v_{b}}{\partial\perp}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Pi_{\wedge\wedge} & = & -\eta_{\parallel}\left(\frac{\partial v_{\perp}}{\partial\perp}+\frac{\partial v_{\wedge}}{\partial\wedge}-\frac{2}{3}\nabla\cdot v\right)+\frac{\eta_{\perp}}{4}\left(\frac{\partial v_{\perp}}{\partial\perp}-\frac{\partial v_{\wedge}}{\partial\wedge}\right)+\frac{\eta_{\times}}{2}\left(\frac{\partial v_{\wedge}}{\partial\perp}+\frac{\partial v_{\perp}}{\partial\wedge}\right)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Pi_{\wedge\perp} & = & -\frac{\eta_{\perp}}{4}\left(\frac{\partial v_{\wedge}}{\partial\perp}+\frac{\partial v_{\perp}}{\partial\wedge}\right)+\frac{\eta_{\times}}{2}\left(\frac{\partial v_{\perp}}{\partial\perp}-\frac{\partial v_{\wedge}}{\partial\wedge}\right)\label{eq:wedgeperp}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Implementation in a Cartesian simulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Preliminary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\perp=\frac{v-\left(v\cdot b\right)b}{\left\Vert v-\left(v\cdot b\right)b\right\Vert }\label{eq:perp}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\wedge=b\times\perp
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\begin{array}{c}
v_{b}\\
v_{\perp}\\
v_{\wedge}
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
b_{x} & b_{y} & b_{z}\\
\perp_{x} & \perp_{y} & \perp_{z}\\
\wedge_{x} & \wedge_{y} & \wedge_{z}
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
v_{x}\\
v_{y}\\
v_{z}
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{c}
v_{x}\\
v_{y}\\
v_{z}
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
b_{x} & b_{y} & b_{z}\\
\perp_{x} & \perp_{y} & \perp_{z}\\
\wedge_{x} & \wedge_{y} & \wedge_{z}
\end{array}\right)^{-1}\left(\begin{array}{c}
v_{b}\\
v_{\perp}\\
v_{\wedge}
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
b_{x} & \perp_{x} & \wedge_{x}\\
b_{y} & \perp_{y} & \wedge_{y}\\
b_{z} & \perp_{z} & \wedge_{z}
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
v_{b}\\
v_{\perp}\\
v_{\wedge}
\end{array}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
b_{x} & b_{y} & b_{z}\\
\perp_{x} & \perp_{y} & \perp_{z}\\
\wedge_{x} & \wedge_{y} & \wedge_{z}
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
b_{x} & \perp_{x} & \wedge_{x}\\
b_{y} & \perp_{y} & \wedge_{y}\\
b_{z} & \perp_{z} & \wedge_{z}
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
b\cdot b & b\cdot\perp & b\cdot\wedge\\
b\cdot\perp & \perp\cdot\perp & \perp\cdot\wedge\\
b\cdot\wedge & \perp\cdot\wedge & \wedge\cdot\wedge
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Therefore [here 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is not changing since we are just looking at the changes due to viscosity],
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\left(\begin{array}{c}
v_{x}\\
v_{y}\\
v_{z}
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
b_{x} & \perp_{x} & \wedge_{x}\\
b_{y} & \perp_{y} & \wedge_{y}\\
b_{z} & \perp_{z} & \wedge_{z}
\end{array}\right)\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\left(\begin{array}{c}
v_{b}\\
v_{\perp}\\
v_{\wedge}
\end{array}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now consider that from (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:one"

\end_inset

), we have such as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
mn\frac{\partial v_{b}}{\partial t}=-\nabla\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
\Pi_{b\perp}\\
\Pi_{b\wedge}\\
\Pi_{bb}
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
\frac{\partial}{\partial\perp}\\
\frac{\partial}{\partial\wedge}\\
\frac{\partial}{\partial b}
\end{array}\right)\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
\Pi_{b\perp}\\
\Pi_{b\wedge}\\
\Pi_{bb}
\end{array}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
mn\frac{\partial v_{x}}{\partial t}=-b_{x}\left(\begin{array}{c}
\frac{\partial}{\partial\perp}\\
\frac{\partial}{\partial\wedge}\\
\frac{\partial}{\partial b}
\end{array}\right)\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
\Pi_{b\perp}\\
\Pi_{b\wedge}\\
\Pi_{bb}
\end{array}\right)-\perp_{x}\left(\begin{array}{c}
\frac{\partial}{\partial\perp}\\
\frac{\partial}{\partial\wedge}\\
\frac{\partial}{\partial b}
\end{array}\right)\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
\Pi_{\perp\perp}\\
\Pi_{\perp\wedge}\\
\Pi_{\perp b}
\end{array}\right)-\wedge_{x}\left(\begin{array}{c}
\frac{\partial}{\partial\perp}\\
\frac{\partial}{\partial\wedge}\\
\frac{\partial}{\partial b}
\end{array}\right)\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
\Pi_{\wedge\perp}\\
\Pi_{\wedge\wedge}\\
\Pi_{\wedge b}
\end{array}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are going to want to regard the viscous effect as a flow of momentum
 from one cell to another, by applying the divergence theorem.
 What we are then aiming to compute in this approach, is the amount of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{x}$
\end_inset

 to send across a cell boundary given the nearby values of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 which determine an estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla v$
\end_inset

, and given 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 at the edge.
 This is not just so we can actually carry it out; we need something we
 can actually insert into 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial\left(v_{e}-v_{i}\right)}{\partial t}=0$
\end_inset

.
 However, getting a linear combination at runtime is sufficient; our algebra
 can anticipate it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Divergence theorem application
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a given coordinate system, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{cell}\nabla\cdot f\mbox{ }dx=\int_{\partial cell}f\cdot\hat{n}=\sum_{edges}f_{avg}\cdot\perp_{(outward)}^{edge}\label{eq:divthm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\perp^{edge}$
\end_inset

 is an outward normal vector that has the length of the edge.
 (For the sign consider a square with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1,0,0\right)$
\end_inset

 as the normal on the right and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(-1,0,0\right)$
\end_inset

 on the left ; 
\begin_inset Formula $\int\frac{\partial f_{x}}{\partial x}$
\end_inset

 gets positive from right.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\perp_{z}^{edge}=0$
\end_inset

 for 2D.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So each negated divergence term in 
\begin_inset Formula $mn\frac{\partial v_{x}}{\partial t}=-\nabla\cdot f$
\end_inset

, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, will represent an INWARD derivative on each edge, summed, 
\series bold
\shape slanted
to determine what is a net flow of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{x}$
\end_inset


\series default
\shape default
 because it will feature in the divergence of the neighbouring cell, equal
 and opposite.
 However, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi$
\end_inset

 is then mostly negative terms; so basically a positive outward gradient
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is contributing to an increase of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 here -- as it should be.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because divergence is invariant to transformations between orthonormal coordinat
e bases,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{c}
\frac{\partial}{\partial b}\\
\frac{\partial}{\partial\perp}\\
\frac{\partial}{\partial\wedge}
\end{array}\right)\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
\Pi_{bb}\\
\Pi_{b\perp}\\
\Pi_{b\wedge}
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\\
\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\\
\frac{\partial}{\partial z}
\end{array}\right)\cdot\left(\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
b_{x} & \perp_{x} & \wedge_{x}\\
b_{y} & \perp_{y} & \wedge_{y}\\
b_{z} & \perp_{z} & \wedge_{z}
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
\Pi_{bb}\\
\Pi_{b\perp}\\
\Pi_{b\wedge}
\end{array}\right)\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so proceeding that way round and applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ref{eq:divthm}\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
mn\frac{\partial v_{x}}{\partial t}+ & = & -\left(b_{x}\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
b_{x} & \perp_{x} & \wedge_{x}\\
b_{y} & \perp_{y} & \wedge_{y}\\
b_{z} & \perp_{z} & \wedge_{z}
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
\Pi_{bb}\\
\Pi_{b\perp}\\
\Pi_{b\wedge}
\end{array}\right)+\perp_{x}\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
b_{x} & \perp_{x} & \wedge_{x}\\
b_{y} & \perp_{y} & \wedge_{y}\\
b_{z} & \perp_{z} & \wedge_{z}
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
\Pi_{\perp b}\\
\Pi_{\perp\perp}\\
\Pi_{\perp\wedge}
\end{array}\right)+\wedge_{x}\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
b_{x} & \perp_{x} & \wedge_{x}\\
b_{y} & \perp_{y} & \wedge_{y}\\
b_{z} & \perp_{z} & \wedge_{z}
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
\Pi_{\wedge b}\\
\Pi_{\wedge\perp}\\
\Pi_{\wedge\wedge}
\end{array}\right)\right)\cdot\perp^{edge}\nonumber \\
 & = & -\left(\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
b_{x} & \perp_{x} & \wedge_{x}\\
b_{y} & \perp_{y} & \wedge_{y}\\
b_{z} & \perp_{z} & \wedge_{z}
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
b_{x}\Pi_{bb}+\perp_{x}\Pi_{\perp b}+\wedge_{x}\Pi_{\wedge b}\\
b_{x}\Pi_{b\perp}+\perp_{x}\Pi_{\perp\perp}+\wedge_{x}\Pi_{\wedge\perp}\\
b_{x}\Pi_{b\wedge}+\perp_{x}\Pi_{\perp\wedge}+\wedge_{x}\Pi_{\wedge\wedge}
\end{array}\right)\right)\cdot\perp^{edge}\label{eq:jibs}\\
 & = & -\left(\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
b_{x} & \perp_{x} & \wedge_{x}\\
b_{y} & \perp_{y} & \wedge_{y}\\
b_{z} & \perp_{z} & \wedge_{z}
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
b_{x}\Pi_{bb}+\perp_{x}\Pi_{\perp b}+\wedge_{x}\Pi_{\wedge b}\\
b_{x}\Pi_{b\perp}+\perp_{x}\Pi_{\perp\perp}+\wedge_{x}\Pi_{\wedge\perp}\\
b_{x}\Pi_{b\wedge}+\perp_{x}\Pi_{\perp\wedge}+\wedge_{x}\Pi_{\wedge\wedge}
\end{array}\right)\right)^{Transpose}\perp^{edge}\\
 & = & -\left(\begin{array}{c}
b_{x}\Pi_{bb}+\perp_{x}\Pi_{\perp b}+\wedge_{x}\Pi_{\wedge b}\\
b_{x}\Pi_{b\perp}+\perp_{x}\Pi_{\perp\perp}+\wedge_{x}\Pi_{\wedge\perp}\\
b_{x}\Pi_{b\wedge}+\perp_{x}\Pi_{\perp\wedge}+\wedge_{x}\Pi_{\wedge\wedge}
\end{array}\right)\cdot\left(\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
b_{x} & b_{y} & b_{z}\\
\perp_{x} & \perp_{y} & \perp_{z}\\
\wedge_{x} & \wedge_{y} & \wedge_{z}
\end{array}\right)\perp^{edge}\right)\label{eq:33}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

This then shows what we could have got by going the other way: putting 
\begin_inset Formula $\perp^{edge}$
\end_inset

 into magnetic coordinates and applying the divergence theorem to div in
 magnetic coordinates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Transformed viscous tensor version
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover we can also put it another way: from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ref{eq:jibs}\right)$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
